english:
  title: On Three Friends
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my native Yongja, there dwells a hidden gentleman of the Kim clan who served at court in his youth. Known for his integrity and aversion to evil, he refused to compromise his principles. When appointed magistrate of provinces, he labored to root out corruption that plagued the people, often saying: "Governing the people is like farming—first pull the weeds that choke the good shoots." Wherever he served, officials and commoners alike trembled before him, none daring to commit wrongdoing.

    When he finally retired to his village, he always carried three tools: a cane fitted with a spade, a knife with a file, and a keen short sickle. He called them his Three Friends. With the spade he cleared the weeds worth clearing, with the sickle he cut the branches needing cutting. Whatever could be carved or polished, he attended to with blade and file. He ensured that beautiful shoots grew straight and tall, arranged in perfect order, while gnarled branches and twisted stalks could not tangle and obscure the garden. Thus his courtyard became luminous and clean, his fields neat and cultivated. The entire village held him as their model.

    Kim Gong, a state examination laureate of the Bureau of War, is also from our village. When he came to the capital, he asked me six or seven times—never ceasing—to write about the Three Friends. Admiring Kim's character and honoring Kim Gong's persistence, how could I refuse with hollow excuses?

    I have heard Confucius say: "There are three friends of benefit and three friends of harm." This teaches people to cultivate learning and carefully examine their friendships. Yet these companions are of my own kind, so despite their beneficial or harmful natures, all can be befriended. But these three objects are not of my kind—how then can they be friends?

    Yet the ancients too befriended those unlike themselves. Bai Juyi made poetry, wine, and zither his three friends. Zeng Duanbo chose nine flowers and wine as his ten friends. Though not of our kind, these suffice to comfort the heart and wash away sorrow—worthy of the name friend.

    But a spade, a blade, a sickle—these are the most humble of things. To see them brings no joy to my eyes; to use them brings no relief to my sorrows. Compared to people, they are my servants, not my friends. Yet there is reason to make them friends.

    A friend exists to aid me. In shared doctrine, a friend strengthens my virtue; in shared purpose, a friend furthers my work. When doctrine aligns and purpose converges, even differences in station need not prevent friendship. My purpose is to abhor evil; their power lies in removing it. Through their strength, I fulfill my aim. How could I not make them friends?

    One who cultivates fine grain must remove weeds; one who plants orchids must prune thorns. So too must one cleanse the heart of greed and desire, and the state of treachery and deceit. Yet the work of cleansing the heart rests upon me; the governance of the state rests upon Heaven. Neither awaits friendship. Only in things that remove evil do we find companions worthy of the name—are these not the three objects?

    Such is the hidden gentleman's way: though his purpose is to root out evil, he cannot wield political power. Thus he governs his own heart within and manifests virtue through his deeds without. His resolve grows firmer, his integrity higher, and together with his cultivated crops and planted flowers, all flourish and bear fruit day by day.

    Compare this with Bai Juyi and Zeng Duanbo, who befriended mere distractions and consolations. Few indeed among them escape utter dissolution of purpose. Therefore, those whom Kim befriended are truly the beneficial friends spoken of by Confucius, while those whom the two poets befriended are truly friends of harm. Alas, my own heart has long been obstructed by worldly desire. How can I obtain the aid of a beneficial friend to clear the thorns and brambles from the garden of my mind?
  footnotes:
    - 'Yongja (永嘉): A region in what is now Zhejiang Province, China, suggesting this may be set in a Chinese context or reflects the Neo-Confucian scholarly tradition.'
    - 'Bai Juyi (白樂天): The famous Tang Dynasty poet known for his accessible verse and philosophical reflections on friendship and art.'
    - 'Zeng Duanbo (曾端伯): A scholar who exemplified unconventional approaches to cultivating virtue through appreciation of natural beauty.'
    - The 'three friends of benefit' and 'three friends of harm' referenced from Confucius refer to friends distinguished by virtue and those that lead one astray—a foundational concept in Confucian ethics.
    - This essay represents a distinctive Neo-Confucian reinterpretation of friendship, extending the concept beyond human relationships to material objects that assist in moral cultivation.
